id="post-4069" class="post-4069 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-food-body-mind tag-farm tag-organic tag-soil"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2013/09/30/soil-benefits-from-organic-farming/" title="Permalink to Soil Benefits from Organic Farming" rel="bookmark">Soil Benefits from Organic Farming</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2013/09/30 10:54 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2013/09/30/soil-benefits-from-organic-farming/" title="Soil Benefits from Organic Farming" rel="bookmark">2013/09/30 10:54 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>The benefits of organic farming keep revealing themselves &#8211; it turns out that the soil itself benefits from farmers growing organic crops.</p><blockquote><p>“Farmers interested in transitioning to organic production will be happy to see that with good management, yields can be the same, with potentially higher returns and better soil quality,” said Delate, who leads the project.</p><p>The U.S. organic ag industry continues to grow and was a $31 billion industry in 2011, Delate said. To market a crop as organic, it must be grown on land that has received no synthetic chemicals for three years prior to harvest.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.organiccouncil.ca/news/study-shows-soil-building-benefits-of-organic-farming">Read more.</a></p><p>Thanks to @ThePeterKelly</p><div
